Ask HN: Feed of Interesting GitHub Projects?
text:
Suppose I was willing to look at 50 or so GitHub projects a day to find ones that I might be interested in or that would have broad community interest. What would be a good feed for this?

(I am using ‘GitHub’ here generically —- I’d be just as happy to find projects hosted elsewhere. Also, I have a filtering system so a feed of 500 a day would be fine if it were machine readable, say RSS.)

Ask HN: Looking for a Cofounder Full Stack Dev
text:
Tl;dr Looking for a technical co-founder for https://coursecopilot.ai/

Background: I've built 2 online course and coaching businesses over the last 7 years. One has sunsetted. The other is currently hovering around US$1.2M ARR. I have a team in place in the current business and I'm not involved in the day-to-day anymore.

Now I want switch gears and dive back into the SaaS world and build a product-based business as opposed to a personal brand facing company.

I'm looking for a technical co-founder to help me build Course Copilot.

I know juuuust enough about basic programming to do it myself (eventually), but it will painfully slow. Speed is critical right now.

My ask: 1. Is this something you're interested in? If yes, reach out. Elif: 2. If you know someone looking to take on a new project, get in touch. Elif: 3. Is there a space or a community that I'm missing that I should be connecting with and reaching out to to find my +1? Break.

I'm also open to any comments or questions about the product and use case. I'd be really interested to hear your insights!

Show HN: I made a Unix timestamp converter that includes micro and nanoseconds
text: I find myself having to convert a lot of nanosecond unix timestamps to a human readable format, and I've noticed most of the online calculators just format to the milliseconds. I've been learning more about frontend development, so I made a converter that also outputs the micro and nanoseconds in the human readable output. I'll take any feedback :)
